Vice President Kamala Harris visited the University of Miami to discuss the importance of addressing the climate crisis. She highlighted the increasing frequency and intensity of extreme weather events and the impact they have on coastal communities. Harris announced that the administration will invest $562 million to fund climate resilient projects in 149 coastal cities, towns, and counties across America. These projects aim to restore natural infrastructure, such as mangroves and oyster reefs, to reduce the impact of storms and hurricanes and protect marine habitats. Harris emphasized that these investments will not only protect the environment but also create jobs and strengthen the economy. She expressed optimism about the ability to tackle the climate crisis and emphasized the importance of collective action in building a better future.